<HEADLINE>
<P>
RELIGION 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In asking the question, "Is the West Blinded by Religion?" (editorial, May 1), 
The Times revealed its own religious blind spot. Calling the "U.N. rescue of 
Muslim Somalia from famine and anarchy" a refutation of the Muslim Public 
Affairs Council's claim that the "United Nations is effective only when it acts 
against Muslims" is specious.Unlike the Bosnians, the Somalians were not 
victims of Christian aggression. 
</P>
<P>
 After 15 years of research on the history of Christianity and racism, I have 
yet to find a case in which the West has effectively opposed a Christian 
nation's oppression of non-Christians. Western culture is driven by the 
Christian dogma that all other faiths are false and therefore all other 
cultures are inferior. That dogma was a justification for not only those famous 
European battles with Muslims, but, when reinforced by the Christian mandate to 
spread the word, for every Western intrusion into the polytheistic world where 
two-thirds of the Earth's people live. 
</P>
<P>
 FORREST G. WOOD 
</P>
<P>
 Bakersfield 
</P>
<P>
 Wood is the author of "The Arrogance of Faith: Christianity and Race in 
America from the Colonial Era to the Twentieth Century" (Knopf).  
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051094-0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 040140 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
