<HEADLINE>
<P>
COUNTYWIDE FOCUS: 7 COUNTY SCHOOLS WIN STATE AWARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MAIA DAVIS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Seven Ventura County schools are among 180 middle schools and high schools 
across the state that have been named California Distinguished Schools this 
year. 
</P>
<P>
 Cabrillo Middle School in the Ventura Unified School District; Medea Creek 
Middle School and Oak Park High School in Oak Park Unified; Charles Blackstock 
and E.O. Green schools in the Hueneme Elementary district; Monte Vista 
Intermediate in the Pleasant Valley Elementary district, and Thousand Oaks High 
School in Conejo Valley received the state honor. 
</P>
<P>
 Thousand Oaks High School Principal Keith Wilson attributed his school's 
success to the combination of parents, students and faculty. "They deserve the 
recognition," he said. 
</P>
<P>
 It was the first time that five of the schools were named distinguished 
schools. 
</P>
<P>
 Medea Creek and Blackstock won the honor two years ago. 
</P>
<P>
 But since that time, the state has changed its criteria for selecting 
distinguished schools. 
</P>
<P>
 When the state Department of Education launched the distinguished-school 
program in 1985, it awarded the honor mainly on the basis of students' scores 
on statewide assessment tests. 
</P>
<P>
 In 1992, however, California students did not take any statewide assessment 
tests for education officials to use as criteria for the 1993 awards. 
</P>
<P>
 So in 1993, the Education Department began to bestow the distinguished-school 
honor based mainly on how well schools implement the state's curriculum 
guidelines. This year, state education officials also put some weight on 
schools' performance last spring on the new California Learning Assessment 
System exams. 
</P>
<P>
 The state names distinguished elementary schools in alternate years to middle 
and high schools. 
</P>
<P>
 Last year, 13 elementary schools in Ventura County received the award: 
Weathersfield in the Conejo Valley district; Bard and Sunkist in Hueneme; Mar 
Vista in Ocean View; El Rancho and Los Primeros structured schools and Las 
Colinas in Pleasant Valley, and six schools in Ventura Unified: Juanamaria, 
Junipero Serra, Lincoln, Loma Vista, Portola and Saticoy. MAIA DAVIS 
</P>
</TEXT>
