<HEADLINE>
<P>
HOMELESS AGAIN; HUD OFFICIALS TAKE BACK DUPLEX OCCUPIED BY PROTESTERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TINA DAUNT 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Homeless protesters who illegally took over a vacant government-owned duplex 
in the Pico-Union district last week were forced to clear out Monday, under the 
threat of prosecution for trespassing. 
</P>
<P>
 Shortly before 3 p.m., officials of the U.S. Department of Housing and Urban 
Development, assisted by several Los Angeles police officers, removed one 
squatter and boarded up the West 17th Place property where four homeless people 
had been living. Officials threatened to arrest anyone who tried to re-enter 
the building. 
</P>
<P>
 The squatters and several advocates for the homeless took over the Los Angeles 
property May 2 as part of a statewide effort to force the federal government to 
turn over abandoned U.S.-owned buildings to the homeless. 
</P>
<P>
 Linda Armstrong, the only person in the duplex when HUD officials arrived, 
agreed to leave without incident. She packed two canvas bags with clothes and 
food -- items donated during her weeklong stay in the run-down duplex -- and 
quietly walked out into the afternoon sun. 
</P>
<P>
 The other homeless people who had been staying at the duplex will have to make 
arrangements with HUD to get their belongs, including blankets and several 
couches, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
 "They'll throw us out, yet this building will stand vacant," Armstrong said. 
"It's not fair." 
</P>
<P>
 In all, nearly a dozen properties from Long Beach to San Francisco were seized 
in an effort organized by the California Homeless Network. 
</P>
<P>
 Charles Ming, area coordinator of HUD's Los Angeles office, said he tried to 
persuade the homeless people last week to leave the property and apply for 
government housing through normal HUD channels. When the squatters ignored his 
request, he said he had no choice but to evict them. 
</P>
<P>
 "What they did was illegal," Ming said. 
</P>
<P>
 Elsewhere, HUD officials and Long Beach police on Monday evicted several 
squatters from two houses taken over in that city. The occupants left without 
incident. 
</P>
<P>
 Rob Leonard, a network member and organizer of the Los Angeles break-in, said 
homeless activists hope the protest will prompt discussion with federal 
officials on the future use of vacant properties. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have a strong moral position," Leonard said. "Although it is technically 
an illegal squat, HUD has the authority to make some kind of arrangement with 
us. . . . Instead they have thrown people onto the streets." TINA DAUNT 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA051094-0156 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 040275 </DOCID>
